{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478296"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:12:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:12:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17330"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17330"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.02,0.09,0.02,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10020"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81012"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"6626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11173"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-week-old boy is brought to the General Practice clinic by his parent for a routine check. Both parents are of Northern European descent. He was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis parents are also your patients and you know that they are considering separating. Both parents look tired and there is obvious discord between them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed though settles with his mother easily. His mother states that the husband forgot to bring the bottle so the baby is due for a feed. During the skin examination, you note a 4 cm blue-grey patch over his sacral area (Image) above mild dermatitis. The patch has poorly defined borders and is non-tender. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable. He otherwise is behaving appropriately for his development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contact child protection services","Urgent dermatology referral","Serial photography","Genetic testing","Documentation and reassurance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with a classic case of dermal melanocytosis, also known as Mongolian spots. These are benign birthmarks caused by melanocytes trapped in the dermis during embryonic migration. While more common in Asian, African, and Hispanic populations, they can occur in any ethnic group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocumentation and reassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. These lesions are entirely benign and typically fade over time, usually disappearing by school age. Parents should be reassured about the benign nature of the condition and that no treatment is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact child protection services\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this scenario. While there is parental discord, there are no signs of abuse or neglect. The blue-grey patch is a normal variant and not a bruise or sign of trauma which would be more tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent dermatology referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessary for this benign condition. Referral would only be warranted if there were atypical features or diagnostic uncertainty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial photography\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for routine monitoring of dermal melanocytosis. While the lesions typically fade with time, there is no medical need to document this progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as dermal melanocytosis is not associated with any genetic syndromes when occurring in isolation. The presence of these spots is a normal variant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising this as a normal variant, documenting its presence in the medical record, and providing appropriate reassurance to parents. The blue-grey colour and typical location on the sacrum or buttocks are characteristic features. It\u0027s important to note that while these lesions are less common in fair-skinned individuals, their presence does not indicate any underlying condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dermal melanocytosis (Mongolian spots) can occur in any ethnic group, though they are less common in people with fair skin.","Dermal melanocytosis presents as blue-grey patches most commonly on the sacral area and buttocks.","These lesions are benign and typically fade by school age, requiring no treatment."],"references":["Ryan E, Warren L. Birthmarks Identification and management. Australian Family Physician. 2012: 41 (5). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/may/birthmarks","Franceschini D, Dinulos JG. Dermal melanocytosis and associated disorders. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2015.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26087431/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17330"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21837"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}}